This paper discusses the use of resistive switching devices for nonvolatile memory applications, which falls under the category of Emerging Technologies (cs.ET). The paper specifically focuses on the use of complementary resistive switches (CRSs) for logic-in-memory operations, which involves circuit design and analysis, placing it under the sub-category of Architecture (cs.AR). The use of SPICE simulations and memristive device models suggests a focus on Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) and Electromagnetics (cs.EM). Finally, the discussion of area consumption and device count suggests a focus on Computer Engineering (cs.CE).
